Philippines Stocks: Metro Pacific, Metropolitan Bank, PLDT

-- B y   I a n   C .   S a y s o n   a n d   Y u d i t h   H o
-- 
2011-08-08T02:35:24Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-08-08/philippines-stocks-metro-pacific-metropolitan-bank-pldt.html
Shares of the following companies had
unusual moves in Philippine trading. Stock symbols are in
parentheses, and prices are as of 10:23 a.m. in  Manila , unless
stated otherwise.  The Philippine Stock Exchange Index sank 115.35 points, or
2.6 percent, to 4,322.20, set for the biggest decline since
February 10.  Banks:  Metropolitan Bank & Trust (MBT)  Co dropped 4.3
percent to 72.95 pesos, bound for the steepest fall since Feb.
10, after central bank governor Amando Tetangco said the
downgrade of the U.S.’s top debt rating may cause capital
outflows from emerging markets, including the  Philippines .  Bank of the Philippine Islands (BPI PM), the nation’s
largest bank by market value, declined 2.3 percent to 58.60
pesos and Banco de Oro Unibank Inc. (BDO PM) retreated 0.8
percent to 60 pesos.  Metro Pacific Investments Corp. (MPI)   fell 2 percent to
3.40 pesos after Chief Financial Officer David Nicol said the
company expects to spend 189.6 billion pesos ($4.45 billion) for
capital expenditure in the next four to five years.  Separately, Metro Pacific’s unit Metro Pacific Tollways
Corp. is “open” to delisting its shares from the stock market,
Metro Pacific Tollways President Ramoncito Fernandez told
reporters on Aug. 5.  Philippine Long Distance Telephone Co. (TEL)   declined
2.5 percent to 2,350 pesos after Chief Justice Renato Corona
said on Aug. 5 the Philippine supreme court will review a ruling
on the company’s foreign ownership.  To contact the reporters on this story:
